### 3.2 Discrete Random Variables

Let \(X\) be a variable which has the following properties:

1. It is a discrete variable and can take only values \(x_{1},\ x_{2},\ldots,\ x_{n}\).
2. The probability that \(X\) assumes \(x_{1},\ x_{2},\ldots,\ x_{n}\) are \(p_{1},\ p_{2},\ldots,\ p_{n}\) respectively.

Then \(X\) is a **discrete random variable** if \(\sum_{i=1}^{n}p_{i}=1\).

A stable showing all the possible occurrences and probabilities is called a **probability distribution table**. The function that allocates probabilities \(\mathrm{P}(X=x)\) is known as the **probability density function (p.d.f) of \(X\).

